resemblance to these ancient, Norse, gods.

00:07:22.351 --> 00:07:25.111
So, how about where they actually lived?

00:07:25.611 --> 00:07:28.151
The Greek and Roman Gods famously

00:07:28.151 --> 00:07:30.461
lived on Mount Olympus, which is,

00:07:30.651 --> 00:07:32.451
in fact, a real mountain - it’s

00:07:32.461 --> 00:07:34.241
the highest mountain in Greece.

00:07:35.021 --> 00:07:38.221
In Norse mythology, the Gods lived

00:07:38.231 --> 00:07:40.331
in a different world altogether.

00:07:41.011 --> 00:07:43.591
It was called Asgard, and it

00:07:43.591 --> 00:07:45.241
was a beautiful place full of

00:07:45.351 --> 00:07:47.401
extravagant palaces where the

00:07:47.401 --> 00:07:48.731
gods would spend their time.

00:07:49.871 --> 00:07:51.171
Alongside Asgard, there

00:07:51.171 --> 00:07:52.951
were eight other worlds.

00:07:53.591 --> 00:07:55.651
One of these worlds was Midgard,

00:07:55.911 --> 00:07:57.991
the home of human beings, the

00:07:57.991 --> 00:08:00.331
world that you and I live in.

00:08:00.641 --> 00:08:02.091
And the world the Vikings

00:08:02.091 --> 00:08:02.951
lived in, of course.

00:08:03.961 --> 00:08:06.661
Another world was called Jotunheim, and

00:08:06.661 --> 00:08:09.641
it was home to evil, powerful giants.

00:08:10.871 --> 00:08:13.181
As well as Asgard, Midgard and

00:08:13.911 --> 00:08:15.861
Jotunheim, the vikings also believed

00:08:15.911 --> 00:08:18.111
in a place called Alfheim, which

00:08:18.111 --> 00:08:20.701
was a world full of elves, and

00:08:20.931 --> 00:08:23.781
Nidavellir, a world full of dwarves.

00:08:24.431 --> 00:08:26.071
Now, perhaps you think this all

00:08:26.071 --> 00:08:28.471
sounds wonderful and you have decided

00:08:28.471 --> 00:08:30.031
that you are going to convert and

00:08:30.151 --> 00:08:32.451
become a believer in Norse mythology.

00:08:33.031 --> 00:08:33.951
Perhaps you think it

00:08:34.111 --> 00:08:35.971
sounds somewhat strange.

00:08:36.101 --> 00:08:37.371
Interesting, but not

00:08:37.561 --> 00:08:39.061
particularly believable.

00:08:39.921 --> 00:08:43.171
In any case, there are only a few thousand

00:08:43.171 --> 00:08:46.731
people in the entire world today who still

00:08:46.741 --> 00:08:49.551
worship the Norse gods, or believe in the

00:08:49.551 --> 00:08:51.971
theory of the Nine Worlds, as it's called.

00:08:52.761 --> 00:08:55.131
It’s no longer a popular religion

00:08:55.131 --> 00:08:57.741
by any means, so what went wrong?

00:08:58.451 --> 00:09:01.451
Well, for this we have to thank,

00:09:01.591 --> 00:09:03.941
or blame perhaps, Christianity.

00:09:04.801 --> 00:09:07.291
As the Vikings started to raid Britain,

00:09:07.541 --> 00:09:09.971
they came into contact with Christianity,

00:09:10.241 --> 00:09:12.811
which was the dominant religion in Britain

00:09:12.951 --> 00:09:14.868
by the time of the Vikings’ arrival.

00:09:15.938 --> 00:09:17.758
Historians believe that there are

00:09:17.778 --> 00:09:20.048
several possible reasons that the

00:09:20.048 --> 00:09:23.108
Vikings embraced Christianity so quickly.

00:09:23.998 --> 00:09:25.738
Perhaps it could have been to do with

00:09:25.748 --> 00:09:27.818
the fact that the Christian ideals

00:09:27.828 --> 00:09:30.908
of love and acceptance, of going to

00:09:30.908 --> 00:09:33.178
heaven and not having to constantly

00:09:33.178 --> 00:09:35.558
fight people in bloody battles, that

00:09:35.778 --> 00:09:38.458
this was alluring, it was attractive.

00:09:39.458 --> 00:09:41.608
Perhaps it was due to the fact that the

00:09:41.608 --> 00:09:45.068
Vikings wanted to assimilate, to blend

00:09:45.078 --> 00:09:47.928
in, with the native, Christian population.

00:09:48.768 --> 00:09:50.948
Perhaps it was after pressure

00:09:50.978 --> 00:09:52.928
from Germans to the south.

00:09:53.668 --> 00:09:55.298
Perhaps it was because they already

00:09:55.298 --> 00:09:57.638
had a hundred or so gods, and they

00:09:57.638 --> 00:09:59.628
figured that adding another one to

00:09:59.628 --> 00:10:01.908
believe in wouldn’t be such a big deal.

00:10:03.508 --> 00:10:06.248
Whatever the true reason, or whatever

00:10:06.248 --> 00:10:09.278
the mix of reasons, relatively soon

00:10:09.458 --> 00:10:11.208
after the Viking raids started,

00:10:11.468 --> 00:10:14.058
the Vikings increasingly started

00:10:14.058 --> 00:10:17.138
to worship a blend, a mixture, of

00:10:17.198 --> 00:10:19.278
Christianity and Norse Mythology.

00:10:20.288 --> 00:10:22.508
Even when the first Christian churches

00:10:22.508 --> 00:10:24.778
were built in Scandinavia, there were

00:10:24.788 --> 00:10:28.148
often Norse gods and creatures carved

00:10:28.168 --> 00:10:30.678
into the wood alongside the pictures of

00:10:30.898 --> 00:10:33.878
Jesus and the cross, and archaeologists

00:10:34.198 --> 00:10:36.788
have also found gravestones with

00:10:36.788 --> 00:10:39.238
the cross of Jesus on one half, and

00:10:39.248 --> 00:10:41.998
the hammer of Thor on the other.

00:10:43.268 --> 00:10:46.148
And with time, Norse mythology

00:10:46.258 --> 00:10:49.248
eventually faded away almost entirely,

00:10:49.368 --> 00:10:51.878
with Christianity taking its place.

00:10:52.748 --> 00:10:55.348
By the fourteenth century, Jesus was

00:10:55.348 --> 00:10:58.208
the dominant force in Scandinavia, and

00:10:58.388 --> 00:11:01.098
the viking gods never really recovered.

00:11:02.288 --> 00:11:05.008
This being said, while belief

00:11:05.028 --> 00:11:07.398
in Norse gods has now all but

00:11:07.398 --> 00:11:09.418
disappeared, their legacy and

00:11:09.578 --> 00:11:11.588
influence is everywhere we look.

00:11:12.378 --> 00:11:14.938
The English language, for example, is

00:11:14.938 --> 00:11:18.018
dotted with references to Norse gods.

00:11:18.478 --> 00:11:20.478
The days of the week are the

00:11:20.478 --> 00:11:22.138
most obvious example of this.

00:11:22.748 --> 00:11:25.458
“ Tuesday” is named after Tyr, the

00:11:25.578 --> 00:11:27.488
god of warriors, the one whose hand

00:11:27.488 --> 00:11:29.068
was bitten off by a giant wolf.

00:11:29.488 --> 00:11:32.038
It literally means the Day of Tyr.

00:11:33.028 --> 00:11:34.958
And it isn’t the only example.

00:11:35.258 --> 00:11:37.808
“Wednesday” is named after Odin,

00:11:38.108 --> 00:11:40.188
who was also known as Wodin.

00:11:40.958 --> 00:11:42.388
“Thursday”, of course,

00:11:42.398 --> 00:11:44.028
is named after Thor.

00:11:44.478 --> 00:11:45.608
And finally we have

00:11:45.818 --> 00:11:47.748
Friday, named after Frigg.

00:11:48.768 --> 00:11:51.098
The other days of the week, as you

00:11:51.098 --> 00:11:53.268
may know, have different origins:

00:11:53.498 --> 00:11:55.418
“Monday” is named after the moon,

00:11:55.538 --> 00:11:57.598
“Sunday” is named after the sun, and

00:11:57.778 --> 00:12:00.148
“Saturday” is named after Saturn.

00:12:00.958 --> 00:12:03.838
But the Norse gods still gave their names

00:12:03.838 --> 00:12:06.268
to more than half of the English days

00:12:06.288 --> 00:12:08.318
of the week, which is pretty impressive

00:12:08.328 --> 00:12:10.838
for a belief system that all but died

00:12:10.848 --> 00:12:13.368
out in Britain over 1,000 years ago.

00:12:14.518 --> 00:12:16.108
And it’s not the only

00:12:16.138 --> 00:12:17.718
influence on English.

00:12:18.038 --> 00:12:19.938
We can see the influence of Norse

00:12:19.938 --> 00:12:22.438
mythology in English place names too.

00:12:23.398 --> 00:12:26.038
In Britain, there are 39 places

00:12:26.198 --> 00:12:29.058
which are named after Odin, or Wodin.

00:12:29.858 --> 00:12:32.338
Places like Wanstead, Wanston and

00:12:32.468 --> 00:12:34.828
Wambrook are all references to the

00:12:34.848 --> 00:12:37.398
old Norse god, even though if you went

00:12:37.398 --> 00:12:39.468
and asked someone on the street there,

00:12:39.478 --> 00:12:42.108
I imagine most wouldn’t realise it.

00:12:42.978 --> 00:12:44.928
And what about the names of people?

00:12:45.298 --> 00:12:46.788
Well, unless you live in

00:12:46.798 --> 00:12:48.758
Scandinavia, you probably don’t

00:12:48.758 --> 00:12:51.448
know anyone called Odin or Thor.

00:12:52.208 --> 00:12:54.188
But do you know anyone called Freya?

00:12:54.508 --> 00:12:57.348
The goddess with a chariot pulled by cats?

00:12:58.098 --> 00:13:00.268
For the past few years, “Freya”

00:13:00.458 --> 00:13:02.288
has been one of the top twenty

00:13:02.288 --> 00:13:04.248
baby names for girls in England.

00:13:04.628 --> 00:13:07.128
I know plenty of Freyas, and it’s

00:13:07.128 --> 00:13:09.078
becoming more and more popular in

00:13:09.088 --> 00:13:10.798
non-English speaking countries too.

00:13:11.728 --> 00:13:14.008
And these are just a few of the

00:13:14.008 --> 00:13:15.878
references to Norse mythology

00:13:15.948 --> 00:13:17.128
in the English language.

